In 1988, the Reagan administration dealt with a drought that
eventually plagued 29% of the nation.  A $3.9 billion relief program
was signed, which was overly generous for thousands of farmers but
ultimately did aid the most needy.  Crop yields plummeted but
commodity prices rose and farm solvency still improved.</SUM>
